\section{Empirical Evidence}

\begin{frame}{Cappelli and Chauvin 1991}
Question: Is there empirical support for the assumptions of the model? 
  \begin{itemize}
  \item use plant-level data taken from internal records of a big automobile company for the year 1982
  \item measure of effort $\rightarrow$ dismissals for disciplinary reasons
  \item higher wage premiums lead to higher levels of discipline (effort) 
  \item higher costs of unemployment higher levels of discipline
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Falk 2007}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item draws on the concept of \emph{reciprocity} $\rightarrow$ a social rule that says people should somehow repay what another person has provided
  \item field experiment which was conducted in collaboration with a charitable organization
  \item sent out roughly 10000 solicitation letters to potential donors $\rightarrow$ manipulated these letters
    \begin{itemize}
    \item one third of the potential donors received the letter without a gift 
    \item one third received the letter together with a small gift 
    \item one third received the letter with a large gift
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
Result: small gift increased the number of donors by 17 percent and large gift increased the number of donors by as much as 75 percent.
\end{frame}

